Definition 3.3. Let $(\mathcal{H},(U^{(t)})_{t},E)$ be a discrete-time or a continuous-time quantum walk. (1) The quantum walk is said to have finite propagation, if for every $t$, the unitary operator $U^{(t)}$ has finite propagation as a morphism from $(\mathcal{H},E)$ to $(\mathcal{H},E)$. (2) The quantum walk is said to be analytic (smooth, or uniform), if for every $t$, the unitary operator $U^{(t)}$ is analytic (smooth, or uniform, respectively) as a morphism from $(\mathcal{H},E)$ to $(\mathcal{H},E)$.
Definition 3.10. We say that $f$ is a continuous morphism of sites if the functor $f^{*}:\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{b})\longrightarrow\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{a})$ preserves sheaves. We denote by $f_{s}:\mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{b},\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{b}})\longrightarrow% \mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})$ the corresponding restriction functor, and by $f^{s}:\mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})\longrightarrow% \mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{b},\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{b}})$ its left adjoint.
Definition 3.4. A cover system $\mathscr{T}$ on $\mathfrak{a}$ is localizing if it satisfies the following: [leftmargin=40pt] (Id) Identity axiom: Given any object $A\in\mathfrak{a}$, the sieve generated by $\text{Id}_{A}$ is a cover for $\mathscr{T}$, i.e. $\mathfrak{a}(-,A)\in\mathscr{T}(A)$ for all $A\in\mathfrak{a}$; (Pb) Pullback axiom: Given a covering sieve $R\subseteq\mathscr{T}(A)$ and $g:A^{\prime}\rightarrow A$ a morphism in $\mathfrak{a}$, the pullback sieve $g^{-1}R$ is also a covering sieve for $\mathscr{T}$. If moreover $\mathscr{T}$ also satisfies the following: (Glue) Glueing axiom: Let $R$ be a sieve on $A$. If there exists a sieve $S$ on $A$ such that for all morphism $g:A^{\prime}\rightarrow A$ in $S$ the pullback sieve $g^{-1}R\in\mathscr{T}(A^{\prime})$, then $R\in\mathscr{T}(A)$; we say $\mathscr{T}$ is a Grothendieck topology.
Definition 2.1. Let $F,G:\mathcal{A}\longrightarrow\mathcal{B}$ be two pseudofunctors between $2$-categories $\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}$. (1) A pseudonatural transformation $\Phi:F\Rightarrow G$ is given by a family of $1$-morphisms $(\Phi_{A}:F(A)\longrightarrow G(A))_{A\in\mathrm{Obj}(\mathcal{A})}$ and a family of invertible $2$-morphisms $(\Phi_{f}:\Phi(A^{\prime})\circ F(f)\Rightarrow G(f)\circ\Phi(A))_{(f:A% \rightarrow A^{\prime})\in\mathcal{A}}$ with the corresponding coherence laws. (2) Given two pseudonatural transformations $\Phi,\Psi:F\Rightarrow G$, a morphism of pseudonatural transformations $r$ between $\Phi$ and $\Psi$ is a modification, that is a family of $2$-morphisms $(r_{A}:\Phi_{A}\Rightarrow\Psi_{A})_{A\in\mathcal{A}}$ such that $(G(f)\circ r_{A})\bullet\Phi_{f}=\Psi_{f}\bullet(r_{A^{\prime}}\circ F(f))$ for all $f:A\longrightarrow A^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{A}$. We denote by $\mathsf{Psnat}(F,G)$ the category of pseudonatural transformations between $F$ and $G$, with morphisms given by the modifications (see [9] or [13]).
Definition 3.2. A cover system $\mathscr{R}$ on $\mathfrak{a}$ consists of providing for each $A\in\mathfrak{a}$ a family of sieves $\mathscr{R}(A)$ on $A$. The sieves in a cover system $\mathscr{R}$ are called covering sieves or covers (for $\mathscr{R}$). We will say that a family $(f_{i}:A_{i}\longrightarrow A)_{i\in I}$ is a cover, or a covering family, if the sieve it generates is a cover.
Definition 5.1. Given $\mathfrak{a},\mathfrak{b}$ two $\alpha$-cocomplete $k$-linear categories, there exists another $\alpha$-cocomplete $k$-linear category $\mathfrak{a}\otimes_{\alpha}\mathfrak{b}$ and a $k$-linear functor $u^{\alpha}_{\mathfrak{a},\mathfrak{b}}:\mathfrak{a}\otimes\mathfrak{b}% \rightarrow\mathfrak{a}\otimes_{\alpha}\mathfrak{b}$ which is $\alpha$-cocontinuous in each variable, such that, for every $\alpha$-cocomplete $k$-linear category $\mathfrak{c}$, composition with $u_{\mathfrak{a},\mathfrak{b}}$ induces an equivalence $\mathsf{Cocont}_{\alpha}(\mathfrak{a}\otimes_{\alpha}\mathfrak{b},\mathfrak{c}% )\cong\mathsf{Cocont}_{\alpha}(\mathfrak{a},\mathsf{Cocont}_{\alpha}(\mathfrak% {b},\mathfrak{c}))$ in $\mathsf{Cat}^{\alpha}(k)$.
Definition 3.6. • A presheaf $F$ on $(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T})$ is an $\mathfrak{a}$-module, this is $F\in\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{a})$. • A sheaf $F$ on $(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T})$ is a presheaf such that the restriction functor $F(A)\cong\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{a})(\mathfrak{a}(-,A),F)\longrightarrow\mathsf% {Mod}(\mathfrak{a})(R,F)$ is an isomorphism for all $A\in\mathfrak{a}$ and all $R\in\mathscr{T}(A)$. We denote by $\mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T})\subseteq\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{a})$ the full subcategory of linear sheaves.
Definition 3.1. Given an object $A\in\mathfrak{a}$, a (linear) sieve on $A$ is a subobject $R$ of the representable module $\mathfrak{a}(-,A)$ in the category $\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{a})$. Given $S=(f_{i}:A_{i}\rightarrow A)_{i\in I}$ a family of morphisms in $\mathfrak{a}$, the sieve generated by $S$ is the smallest sieve $R$ on $A$ such that $f_{i}\in R(A_{i})$ for all $i\in I$.
Definition 3.11 ([18, Def 3.4]). Consider a $k$-linear functor $f:\mathfrak{a}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{c}$. (1) Suppose $\mathfrak{c}$ is endowed with a cover system $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$. We say that $f:\mathfrak{a}\longrightarrow(\mathfrak{c},\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{c}})$ satisfies (G) if for every $C\in\mathfrak{c}$ there is a covering family $(f(A_{i})\longrightarrow C)_{i}$ for $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$. (2) Suppose $\mathfrak{a}$ is endowed with a cover system $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$. We say that $f:(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})\longrightarrow\mathfrak{c}$ satisfies (F) if for every $c:f(A)\longrightarrow f(A^{\prime})$ in $\mathfrak{c}$ there exists a covering family $a_{i}:A_{i}\longrightarrow A$ for $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$ and $f_{i}:A_{i}\longrightarrow A^{\prime}$ with $cf(a_{i})=f({f}_{i})$; (FF) if for every $a:A\longrightarrow A^{\prime}$ in $\mathfrak{a}$ with $f(a)=0$ there exists a covering family $a_{i}:A_{i}\longrightarrow A$ for $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$ with $aa_{i}=0$. (3) Suppose $\mathfrak{a}$ and $\mathfrak{c}$ are endowed with cover systems $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$ and $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$ respectively. We say that $f:(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}})\longrightarrow(\mathfrak{c},% \mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{c}})$ satisfies (LC) if $f$ satisfies (G) with respect to $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$, (F) and (FF) with respect to $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}$, and we further have $\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{a}}=f^{-1}\mathscr{T}_{\mathfrak{c}}$. We denote the class of LC morphisms by $\mathsf{LC}$.
Definition 3.5. A linear site is a pair $(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T})$ where $\mathfrak{a}$ is a $k$-linear category and $\mathscr{T}$ is a Grothendieck topology on $\mathfrak{a}$.
Definition 2.2 ([9, Thm. 1.19]). Given a pseudofunctor $F:\mathcal{I}\rightarrow\mathsf{Cat}$, where $\mathcal{I}$ is a $2$-filtered $2$-category1The bicolimit and its construction actually work when the indexing category is a pre $2$-filtered $2$-category, which is a weaker notion than that of $2$-filtered $2$-category, as pointed out in the introduction of [9]., the 2-filtered bicolimit of $F$ is a category $\mathcal{B}$ together with a pseudonatural transformation $F\Rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ from $F$ to the constant $2$-functor $\mathcal{I}\rightarrow\mathsf{Cat}$ taking the value $\mathcal{B}$ such that, for every category $\mathcal{C}$, it induces via composition an isomorphism of categories $\mathsf{Cat}(\mathcal{B},\mathcal{C})=\mathsf{Psnat}(F,\mathcal{C})$ between the category of functors $\mathcal{B}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ and the category of pseudonatural transformations between the pseudofunctor $F$ and the constant $2$-functor taking the value $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 3.7. Consider a small $k$-linear category $\mathfrak{a}$. A Grothendieck topology $\mathscr{T}$ on $\mathfrak{a}$ is called subcanonical if for every $A\in\mathfrak{a}$, the representable presheaf $\mathfrak{a}(-,A)\in\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{a})$ is a sheaf, this is, it belongs to $\mathsf{Sh}(\mathfrak{a},\mathscr{T})$. The largest Grothendieck subcanonical topology is called the canonical topology.
Definition 3.3. Given $R$ a sieve on $A\in\mathfrak{a}$ and $g:A^{\prime}\rightarrow A$ a morphism in $\mathfrak{a}$, the pullback of $R$ along $g$, denoted $g^{-1}R$, is the sieve on $A^{\prime}$ obtained as the pullback $\tikzcd g^{-1}R\arrow[r,hook]\arrow[d]&\mathfrak{a}(-,A^{\prime})\arrow[d,"g% \circ\,-"]\\ R\arrow[r,hook]&\mathfrak{a}(-,A)$ in $\mathsf{Mod}(\mathfrak{a})$. In particular, we have that $g^{-1}R(A^{\prime\prime})=\{f:A^{\prime\prime}\rightarrow A^{\prime}\,\,|\,\,g% \circ f\in R(A^{\prime\prime})\}$ for all $A^{\prime\prime}\in\mathfrak{a}$.
Definition 6.4. Given cocontinuous functors $F:\mathcal{A}\longrightarrow\mathcal{C}$ and $F^{\prime}:\mathcal{B}\longrightarrow\mathcal{D}$ as above, we define $F\boxtimes F^{\prime}:\mathcal{A}\boxtimes\mathcal{B}\longrightarrow\mathcal{C% }\boxtimes\mathcal{D}$ to be the functor associated to the pseudonatural transformation $F_{\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}}\Rightarrow\mathcal{C}\boxtimes\mathcal{D}$ above via the universal property of $\mathcal{L}(F_{\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}})$.
Definition 2.3. The paths operad $\mathcal{M}$ has natural numbers as colours. The set of operations is $\mathcal{M}(n_{1},\ldots,n_{k};n)=\mathbf{Cat}_{*,*}(\langle n+1\rangle,% \langle n_{1}+1\rangle\times\cdots\times\langle n_{k}+1\rangle),$ and the operad substitution maps being induced by cartesian product and composition in $\mathbf{Cat}_{*,*}.$
Definition 2.2. A cosimplicial monoid in ${\bf V}$ is a cosimplicial object in the category of monoids in ${\bf V}$ that is a functor $E:{\mathbb{\Delta}}\longrightarrow{\bf Mon}({\bf V}),\ E(n)=E([n]).$ A commutative cosimplicial monoid is a cosimplicial object in the category ${\bf Com}({\bf V}).$
Definition 2.1. [GJ, Definition 3.1] An additive category $\mathcal{A}$ is called $n$-abelian category if it satisfies the following axioms: (A0) The category $\mathcal{A}$ is idempotent complete. (A1) Every morphism in $\mathcal{A}$ has an $n$-kernel and an $n$-cokernel. (A2) For every monomorphism $f^{0}\colon X^{0}\to X^{1}$ in $\mathcal{A}$, and for every $n$-cokernel $(f^{1},f^{2},\cdots,f^{n})$, the following sequence is $n$-exact: $X^{0}\xrightarrow{f^{0}}X^{1}\xrightarrow{f^{1}}\cdots\xrightarrow{f^{n-1}}X^{% n}\xrightarrow{f^{n}}X^{n+1}.$ (A2${}^{op}$) For every epimorphism $g^{n}\colon X^{n}\to X^{n+1}$ in $\mathcal{A}$, and for every $n$-kernel $(g^{0},g^{1},\cdots,g^{n-1})$, the following sequence is $n$-exact: $X^{0}\xrightarrow{g^{0}}X^{1}\xrightarrow{g^{1}}\cdots\xrightarrow{g^{n-1}}X^{% n}\xrightarrow{g^{n}}X^{n+1}.$
Definition 5.1. Let $R$ be a ring. Two elements $a,b\in R$ are said to be conjugate if there exists an invertible element $c\in R$ such that $a=cbc^{-1}$. An element $e\in R$ is called idempotent if $e^{2}=e$. Two idempotents $e_{1},e_{2}\in R$ are said to be orthogonal, if $e_{1}e_{2}=e_{2}e_{1}=0$. An idempotent $e\in R$ is called primitive if it is non-zero and can not be decomposed as a sum of two orthogonal non-zero idempotents.
Definition 5.15. Let $t\in\mathbb{C}$. We denote by $\mathcal{D}(t)$ the full subcategory of $\mathop{\mathrm{\underline{Rep}}}(O_{t}^{+})$ with objects $\{(A,e)\in\mathop{\mathrm{\underline{Rep}}}(O_{t}^{+})\mid A=\bigoplus_{i=1}^{% l}[k_{i}],k_{i}\in\mathbb{N}_{0}\text{ even, for any }1\leq i\leq l\}.$
