Definition 4.10 (See [Kn07, Â§8]). Let $k,l\in\mathbb{N}_{0}$ with $k\leq l$ and let $e:\underline{k}\hookrightarrow\underline{l}$ be an injective map. We define two maps $e_{*}:P(l)\to P(k)\text{ and }e^{*}:P(k)\to P(l)$ as follows. For any $p\in P(l)$ we label the points from the left to the right by $\underline{l}$. Then we define $e_{*}(p)\in P(k)$ as the restriction of $p$ to the points in $e(\underline{k})$. For any $q\in P(k)$ we define $e^{*}(q)\in P(l)$ as the partition with $e_{*}(e^{*}(q))=q$ such that all points in $\underline{l}\backslash e(\underline{k})$ are singletons. Moreover, we define a scalar $w_{e}:=\sum_{\begin{subarray}{c}q\in P(l)\\ e_{*}(q)=s_{k}\end{subarray}}\mu_{P}(q,s_{l})\cdot t^{\#q-k}\in\mathbb{C}.$
Definition 3.1 ([BC07, Def. 4.2.]). For any category of partitions $\mathcal{C}$, we introduce the short-hand notation $\mathcal{C}(k)=\mathcal{C}(0,k)$, denoting the partitions in $\mathcal{C}$ with no upper points. The Gram matrices are given by $G^{(k)}:=(t^{l(p^{*},q)})_{p,q\in\mathcal{C}(k)}\quad\text{for all }k\in% \mathbb{N}_{0}.$
Definition 4.19. For any group-theoretical category of partitions $\mathcal{C}$, any $k,l\in\mathbb{N}_{0}$ and any partition $p\in\mathcal{C}(k,l)$, we define recursively $x_{p}:=p-\sum_{q\lneq p}x_{q}\quad\in\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathop{\mathrm{\underline{% Rep}}}(\mathcal{C},t)}([k],[l]).$
Definition 2.4 (Interpolating partition categories). For any category of partitions $\mathcal{C}$ and $t\in\mathbb{C}$ the category $\mathop{\mathrm{\underline{Rep}}}_{0}(\mathcal{C},t)$ has: Objects: $\displaystyle[k],k\in\mathbb{N}_{0},$ Morphisms: $\displaystyle\mathrm{Hom}([k],[l])=\mathbb{C}\mathcal{C}(k,l),$ Composition: $\displaystyle\circ:\mathrm{Hom}([l],[m])\times\mathrm{Hom}([k],[l])\to\mathrm{% Hom}([k],[m])$ $\displaystyle\text{ with }q\circ p=t^{l(q,p)}\leavevmode\nobreak\ qp\text{ for% all }p,q\in\mathcal{C}(k,l)$ The interpolating partition category $\mathop{\mathrm{\underline{Rep}}}(\mathcal{C},t)$ is the Karoubi envelope or (pseudo-abelian completion) of $\mathop{\mathrm{\underline{Rep}}}_{0}(\mathcal{C},t)$, that is, the idempotent completion of the additive completion.
Definition 4.1 ([NS06, Def. 9.15.]). Let $(L,\leq)$ be a finite partially ordered set (poset). For two elements $u,v\in L$ we consider the set $\{w\in L\mid w\leq u,w\leq v\}$. If the maximum of this set exists, it is called the meet of $p$ and $q$ and denoted by $p\wedge q$. If any two elements of $L$ have a meet, then $(L,\wedge)$ is called the meet-semilattice of $L$.
Definition 5.22. Let $k,l\in\mathbb{N}_{0}$ and $p\in P(k,l)$. A block of $p$ is called through-block if it contains upper points as well as lower points.
Definition 5.3. For any algebra $B$, we denote by $\Lambda(B)$ the set of equivalence classes of primitive idempotents of $B$ up to conjugation.
Definition 4.6 ([NS06, Ch. 9]). Let $k,l\geq 0$, and partitions $p,q\in P(k,l)$ on $k+l$ points. We write $p\leq q$ if and only if each block of $q$ is completely contained in one of the blocks of $p$. The induced partial order is called the refinement order.
Definition 5.16 ([NS06, Ex. 9.42.]). Let $k,l\in\mathbb{N}$. To any partition $p\in NC_{2}(2k,2l)$ we associate a partition $\widehat{p}\in NC(k,l)$ as follows. For any odd upper point $m\in\{1,3,\ldots,2k-1\}$, we insert a new point to the right of $m$. Similarly, for any odd lower point $m^{\prime}\in\{1^{\prime},3^{\prime},\ldots,(2k-1)^{\prime}\}$, we insert a new point on the right of $m^{\prime}$. Then $\widehat{p}\in NC(k,l)$ is the coarsest partition on all new points such that no strings of the nested partitions cross. Note that this definition is independent of the choice of the occurring diagrams. Moreover, we set $\widehat{\mathrm{id}_{0}}=\mathrm{id}_{0}$.
Definition 3 If the above condition holds, then the structure $\mathfrak{S}_{1}$ is called finer than $\mathfrak{S}_{2}$ (written $\mathfrak{S}_{1}\geq\mathfrak{S}_{2}$) and $\mathfrak{S}_{2}$ is called coarser than $\mathfrak{S}_{2}$ (written $\mathfrak{S}_{2}\leq\mathfrak{S}_{1}$).
Definition 1 A structure in $\left(\mathcal{C},\left|.\right|,\mathcal{X}\right)$ is an equivalence class of objects of $\mathcal{C}$ with respect to the following equivalence relation: two objects $A$ and $A^{\prime}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ are equivalent if $\left|A\right|=\left|A^{\prime}\right|$ and there is a $\mathcal{C}$-isomorphism $A\rightarrow A^{\prime}.$
Definition 6 If the source $\left(f_{i}:A\rightarrow A_{i}\right)_{i\in I}$ is initial, then the structure of $A$ is called initial with respect to the family $\left(f_{i}:\left|A\right|\rightarrow\left|A_{i}\right|\right)_{i\in I}.$
Definition 2 The structures $\mathfrak{S}_{1}$ and $\mathfrak{S}_{2}$ are called isomorphic if the above condition holds.
Definition 4.8 (Representations of a crossed module of Leibniz algebras). A representation of a crossed module of Leibniz algebras $(\mathfrak{k},\mathfrak{g},\pi,\cdot)$ is a vector space $M$ endowed with a $\mathfrak{g}$-action $\ast$ and a linear map $\delta_{0}\colon M\to M\otimes\mathfrak{k}$ which is • of square zero, i.e. $(\delta_{0}\otimes\mathfrak{k})\circ\delta_{0}=0$, and • $\mathfrak{g}$-equivariant, in the sense of $\delta_{0}(m\ast g)=\delta_{0}(m)\ast g$, where $\mathfrak{g}$ acts on $M\otimes\mathfrak{k}$ according to the Leibniz rule: $(m\otimes k)\ast g=m\otimes k\cdot g+m\ast g\otimes k$. The category of such representations (with the obvious notion of morphisms) is denoted by $\mathcal{M}(\mathfrak{k},\mathfrak{g},\pi,\cdot)$, or simply $\mathcal{M}(\mathfrak{k},\mathfrak{g})$.
Definition 3.3 (Crossed modules of shelves and racks). • A shelf/rack morphism between shelves/racks $(R,\mathrel{\lhd})$ and $(S,\mathrel{\lhd})$ is a map $f\colon R\to S$ intertwining their shelf operations: $f(r\mathrel{\lhd}r^{\prime})=f(r)\mathrel{\lhd}f(r^{\prime}).$ Shelf/rack iso-, endo- and automorphisms are defined analogously. • Given a shelf $(S,\mathrel{\lhd})$, an $S$-set is a set $M$ with a map $\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft}\colon M\times S\to M$ (sometimes seen as a map $\varphi\colon S\to\operatorname{End}_{\mathbf{Set}}(M)$) satisfying $\displaystyle(m\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft}s)\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft}s^{\prime}$ $\displaystyle=(m\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft}s^{\prime})\mathrel{% \blacktriangleleft}(s\mathrel{\lhd}s^{\prime}),$ $\displaystyle m\in M,\,s,s^{\prime}\in S.$ • Given a rack $(R,\mathrel{\lhd})$, an $R$-rack-set is an $R$-set $M$ on which $R$ acts by bijections, i.e., the maps $m\mapsto m\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft}r$ are invertible for all $r\in R$. • The maps $\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft}$ above are called shelf/rack actions. • $S$-modules (or $R$-rack-modules) in an arbitrary category $\mathcal{C}$ are defined as maps $\varphi\colon S\to\operatorname{End}_{\mathcal{C}}(M)$ (or $\varphi\colon R\to\operatorname{Aut}_{\mathbf{Set}}(M)$) satisfying $\varphi(s)\varphi(s^{\prime})=\varphi(s^{\prime})\varphi(s\mathrel{\lhd}s^{% \prime})$. • A crossed module of shelves is the data of a shelf morphism $\pi\colon R\to S$ and a shelf action $\cdot$ of $S$ on $R$ by shelf morphisms, compatible in the sense of $\displaystyle r\cdot\pi(r^{\prime})$ $\displaystyle=r\mathrel{\lhd}r^{\prime},$ $\displaystyle r,r^{\prime}\in R,$ $\displaystyle\pi(r\cdot s)$ $\displaystyle=\pi(r)\mathrel{\lhd}s,$ $\displaystyle r\in R,\,s\in S.$ • If $R$ and $S$ above are racks, with $S$ acting by rack automorphisms, one talks about a crossed module of racks. • An augmented rack is the data of a group $G$, a $G$-set $R$, and a $G$-equivariant map $\pi\colon R\to G$, in the sense of (6).
Definition 2.1 (Braided vocabulary). • A rank $r$ braided system in $\mathcal{C}$ is a family $V_{1},V_{2},\ldots,V_{r}$ of objects of $\mathcal{C}$ endowed with a (multi-)braiding, i.e., morphisms $\sigma_{i,j}=\sigma_{V_{i},V_{j}}\colon V_{i}\otimes V_{j}\to V_{j}\otimes V_{% i},\quad 1\leq{i\leq j}\leq r,$ satisfying the colored Yang-Baxter equation $\displaystyle(\sigma_{j,k}\otimes V_{i})\circ(V_{j}\otimes\sigma_{i,k})\circ(% \sigma_{i,j}\otimes V_{k})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(V_{k}\otimes\sigma_{i,j})\circ(\sigma_{i,k}\otimes V_{j})\circ(V% _{i}\otimes\sigma_{j,k})$ on all the tensor products $V_{i}\otimes V_{j}\otimes V_{k}$ with $1\leq{i\leq j\leq k}\leq r$. Such a system is denoted by $((V_{i})_{1\leq i\leq r};(\sigma_{i,j})_{1\leq i\leq j\leq r})$ or briefly $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$. • Rank $1$ braided systems are called braided objects in $\mathcal{C}$. • A (right) braided module over a braided system $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$ is an object $M$ equipped with morphisms $\overline{\rho}:=(\rho_{i}:M\otimes V_{i}\rightarrow M)_{1\leq i\leq r}$ satisfying, for all $1\leq i\leq j\leq r$, $\displaystyle\rho_{j}\circ(\rho_{i}\otimes V_{j})$ $\displaystyle=\rho_{i}\circ(\rho_{j}\otimes V_{i})\circ(M\otimes\sigma_{i,j}).$ Here both morphisms go from $M\otimes V_{i}\otimes V_{j}$ to $M$. • A morphism between braided modules $(M,\overline{\rho})$ and $(M^{\prime},\overline{\rho^{\prime}})$ over $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$ is a morphism $\varphi\in\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(M,M^{\prime})$ respecting the module structures, in the sense of $\displaystyle\varphi\circ\rho_{i}$ $\displaystyle=\rho^{\prime}_{i}\circ(\varphi\otimes V_{i}).$ • The category of braided modules and their morphisms is denoted by $\mathbf{Mod}_{(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})}$. (Right) braided comodules, their morphisms, and the category $\mathbf{Mod}^{(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})}$ are defined in an analogous way. • A braided (co)module structure on the unit object $\mathbf{I}$ is referred to as a braided (co)character.
Definition 5.5. The unit object $\mathbf{I}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ endowed with a YD module structure over a rank $2$ braided system in $\mathcal{C}$ is called a Yetter-Drinfel${}^{\prime}$d character of the system.
Definition 3.18. The categories described in the proposition are denoted by $\mathcal{M}^{\operatorname{tw}}_{\bullet}(R,S)$, or $\mathcal{M}^{\operatorname{R;tw}}_{\bullet}(R,S)$ in the rack case. Their objects are called twisted representations of the corresponding crossed module of shelves/ racks, and the maps $f$ are referred to as the twisting maps.
Definition 5.13 (Categorical vocabulary). • A pre-tensor category is a category $\mathcal{C}$ endowed with a tensor product, i.e., a bifunctor $\otimes\colon\mathcal{C}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ and natural isomorphisms $\big{(}\,\alpha_{U,V,W}\colon(U\otimes V)\otimes W\overset{\sim}{\to}U\otimes(% V\otimes W)\,\big{)}_{U,V,W\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C})},$ called associator, or associativity constraint, satisfying the pentagon axiom $\xymatrix@R=0.25cm@C=0.6cm{&((U\otimes V)\otimes W)\otimes X\ar[dl]_{-}{\alpha% _{U,V,W}\otimes X\quad}\ar[ddr]^{\alpha_{U\otimes V,W,X}}&\\ (U\otimes(V\otimes W))\otimes X\ar[dd]_{\alpha_{U,V\otimes W,X}}&&\\ &&(U\otimes V)\otimes(W\otimes X)\ar[ddl]^{\alpha_{U,V,W\otimes X}}\\ U\otimes((V\otimes W)\otimes X)\ar[dr]_{-}{U\otimes\alpha_{V,W,X}\quad}&&\\ &U\otimes(V\otimes(W\otimes X))&}$ • A pre-tensor category is called tensor, or monoidal, if endowed with a unit, i.e., an object $I$ in $\mathcal{C}$ and natural isomorphisms $\big{(}\,\lambda_{V}\colon I\otimes V\overset{\sim}{\to}V,\;\rho_{V}\colon V% \otimes I\overset{\sim}{\to}V\,\big{)}_{V\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C})},$ called left and right unitors, or a unit constraint, satisfying the triangle axiom $\xymatrix@R=0.25cm@C=0.6cm{(V\otimes I)\otimes W\ar[rr]^{\alpha_{V,I,W}}\ar[dr% ]_{\rho_{V}\otimes W}&&V\otimes(I\otimes W)\ar[dl]^{{V}\otimes\lambda_{W}}\\ &V\otimes W&}$ • A (pre-)tensor category is called strict if all the constraints are the identity morphisms. • A (pre-)tensor category is called braided if it is endowed with a braiding, or commutativity constraint, i.e. natural isomorphisms $\big{(}\,c_{V,W}\colon V\otimes W\overset{\sim}{\to}W\otimes V\,\big{)}_{V,W% \in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C})}$ respecting the tensor product, in the sense of the hexagon axioms $\xymatrix@R=0.25cm@C=0.7cm{&U\otimes(V\otimes W)\ar[r]^{c_{U,V\otimes W}}&(V% \otimes W)\otimes U\ar[dr]^{\alpha_{V,W,U}}&\\ (U\otimes V)\otimes W\ar[dr]_{-}{c_{U,V}\otimes W\quad}\ar[ur]^{\alpha_{U,V,W}% }&&&V\otimes(W\otimes U)\\ &(V\otimes U)\otimes W\ar[r]_{\alpha_{V,U,W}}&V\otimes(U\otimes W)\ar[ur]_{% \quad V\otimes c_{U,W}}&}$ $\xymatrix@R=0.25cm@C=0.7cm{&(U\otimes V)\otimes W\ar[r]^{c_{U\otimes V,W}}&W% \otimes(U\otimes V)\ar[dr]^{\alpha^{-1}_{W,U,V}}&\\ U\otimes(V\otimes W)\ar[dr]_{-}{U\otimes c_{V,W}\quad}\ar[ur]^{\alpha^{-1}_{U,% V,W}}&&&(W\otimes U)\otimes V\\ &U\otimes(W\otimes V)\ar[r]_{\alpha^{-1}_{U,W,V}}&(U\otimes W)\otimes V\ar[ur]% _{\quad c_{U,W}\otimes V}&}$
Definition 3.1. A rack is a shelf $(R,\mathrel{\lhd})$ for which all the right translations $t_{r}\colon r^{\prime}\mapsto r^{\prime}\mathrel{\lhd}r$ are bijective; their inverses are denoted by $r^{\prime}\mapsto r^{\prime}\mathrel{\widetilde{\lhd}}r$.
Definition 4.1 (Crossed modules of Leibniz algebras). • A unital Leibniz algebra morphism between unital Leibniz algebras $(\mathfrak{k},\,[,]_{\mathfrak{k}}\,,1_{\mathfrak{k}})$ and $(\mathfrak{g},\,[,]_{\mathfrak{g}}\,,1_{\mathfrak{g}})$ is a linear map $f\colon\mathfrak{k}\to\mathfrak{g}$ intertwining their structures: $\displaystyle f([k,k^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{k}})$ $\displaystyle=[f(k),f(k^{\prime})]_{\mathfrak{g}},$ $\displaystyle f(1_{\mathfrak{k}})$ $\displaystyle=1_{\mathfrak{g}}.$ • A derivation of a unital Leibniz algebra $(\mathfrak{k},\,[,]_{\mathfrak{k}}\,,1_{\mathfrak{k}})$ is a linear map $f\colon\mathfrak{k}\to\mathfrak{k}$ satisfying $\displaystyle f([k,k^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{k}})$ $\displaystyle=[k,f(k^{\prime})]_{\mathfrak{k}}+[f(k),k^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{k}},$ $\displaystyle f(1_{\mathfrak{k}})$ $\displaystyle=0.$ • A representation of $(\mathfrak{k},\,[,]_{\mathfrak{k}}\,,1_{\mathfrak{k}})$ is a vector space $M$ together with a unital Leibniz algebra morphism $\varphi\colon\mathfrak{k}\to\operatorname{End}_{\Bbbk}(M)$ (cf. Example 2.5 for the Leibniz structure on $\operatorname{End}_{\Bbbk}(M)$). One says that $\mathfrak{k}$ acts on $M$, and writes $m\cdot k=\varphi(k)(m)$. • All the definitions above admit obvious non-unital versions. • A crossed module of Leibniz algebras is the data of a Leibniz algebra morphism $\pi\colon\mathfrak{k}\to\mathfrak{g}$ and a (right) $\mathfrak{g}$-action $\cdot$ on $\mathfrak{k}$ by derivations, compatible in the sense of $\displaystyle k\cdot\pi(k^{\prime})$ $\displaystyle=[k,k^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{k}},$ $\displaystyle k,k^{\prime}\in\mathfrak{k},$ $\displaystyle\pi(k\cdot g)$ $\displaystyle=[\pi(k),g]_{\mathfrak{g}},$ $\displaystyle k\in\mathfrak{k},\,g\in\mathfrak{g}.$
Definition 2.8 (Generalized YD modules). • Let $(C,A;\sigma_{C,C},\sigma_{A,A},\sigma_{C,A})$ be a braided system in $\mathcal{C}$. A (right-right) Yetter-Drinfel${}^{\prime}$d module over this system is an object $M$ of $\mathcal{C}$ with a right $(A;\sigma_{A,A})$-module structure $\rho$ and a right $(C;\sigma_{C,C})$-comodule structure $\delta$, compatible in the sense of $\displaystyle\delta\circ\rho$ $\displaystyle=(\rho\otimes C)\circ(M\otimes\sigma_{C,A})\circ(\delta\otimes A).$ • A morphism between two YD modules over the same braided system is a morphism in $\mathcal{C}$ preserving the module and the comodule structures (cf. (10)). • The category of YD modules over $(C,A;\overline{\sigma})$ and their morphisms is denoted by $\mathcal{Y}\mathcal{D}_{A}^{C}$.
Definition 5.2 (Enriching structures). Take a braided system $(C,A;\overline{\sigma})$ in $\mathcal{C}$. Denote by $\mathcal{Z}_{A}^{C}$ the category whose • objects are the enriching structures for $(C,A;\overline{\sigma})$, i.e., objects $M$ together with morphisms $\sigma_{C,M}$ and $\sigma_{M,A}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ such that $(C,M,A;$ $\overline{\sigma},\sigma_{C,M},\operatorname{Id}_{M\otimes M},\sigma_{M,A})$ is a braided system; • morphisms are those morphisms $\varphi\colon M\to M^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ which satisfy the naturality conditions $\displaystyle(\varphi\otimes C)\circ\sigma_{C,M}$ $\displaystyle=\sigma_{C,M^{\prime}}\circ(C\otimes\varphi),$ $\displaystyle(A\otimes\varphi)\circ\sigma_{M,A}$ $\displaystyle=\sigma_{M^{\prime},A}\circ(\varphi\otimes A).$
Definition 3.8 (Representations of a crossed module of shelves/racks). • A set-theoretic / linear representation of a crossed module of shelves $(R,S,\pi,\cdot)$ is an $S$-module $(M,\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft})$ in $\mathbf{Set}$ / in $\mathbf{Vect}_{\Bbbk}$, endowed with an $R$-grading satisfying the compatibility condition $M_{r}\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft}s\subseteq M_{r\cdot s}.$ The category of such representations (with the obvious notion of morphisms) is denoted by $\mathcal{M}_{\mathbf{Set}}(R,S,\pi,\cdot)$, or simply $\mathcal{M}_{\mathbf{Set}}(R,S)$ when this does not lead to confusion. The notation $\mathcal{M}_{\Bbbk}(\ldots)$ is used in the linear setting. • If $(R,S,\pi,\cdot)$ above is a crossed module of racks and $(M,\mathrel{\blacktriangleleft})$ is an $S$-rack-module, then we talk about representations of a crossed module of racks and use the notations $\mathcal{M}^{\operatorname{R}}_{\bullet}(\ldots)$.
Definition 2.1. Fix an infinite cardinal $\mu$. A $\mu$-ary language $L$ consists of a set of function symbols $\langle F_{i}:i\in I_{F}\rangle$ and relations $\langle R_{j}:j\in J_{R}\rangle$ (here, $I_{F}$, $J_{R}$ are index sets) so that each symbol has an arity, denoted $n(F_{i})$ or $n(R_{j})$, where $n$ is an ordinal valued function $n:\{R_{j},F_{i}\mid i\in I_{F},j\in J_{R}\}\rightarrow\mu$. Given a $\mu$-ary language $L$, an $L$-structure $M$ is $\langle|M|,F^{M}_{i},R^{M}_{j}\rangle_{i\in L_{F},j\in L_{R}}$ where $|M|$ is a set, called the universe of $M$; $F^{M}_{i}:{}^{n(F_{i})}|M|\to|M|$ is a function of arity $n(F_{i})$; and $R^{M}_{j}\subset{}^{n(R_{j})}|M|$ is a relation of arity $n(R_{j})$. We say that $\langle\operatorname{\mathcal{K}},\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}\rangle$ is a $\mu$-abstract class provided (1) $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ is a class of $L$-structure for a fixed $\mu$-ary language $L:=\operatorname{L}(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}})$. (2) $\langle\operatorname{\mathcal{K}},\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}\rangle$ is a partially pre-ordered class (that is, $\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}$ is reflexive and transitive) such that $M\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}N$ implies that $M$ is an $L$-submodel of $N$. (3) $\langle\operatorname{\mathcal{K}},\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}\rangle$ respects $L$-isomorphisms; that is, if $f:N\to N^{\prime}$ is an $L$-isomorphism and $N\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$, then $N^{\prime}\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ and if we also have $M\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ with $M\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}N$, then $f(M)\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ and $f(M)\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}N^{\prime}$; We often do not make the distinction between $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ and $(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}},\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}})$.
Definition 6.5. Let $\delta$ be an ordinal. An abstract class $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ has the $\delta$-chain extension property if for every chain $\langle M_{i}:i<\delta\rangle$, there exists $M_{\delta}\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ such that $M_{i}\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}M_{\delta}$ for all $i<\delta$. We say that $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ has the chain extension property if it has the $\delta$-chain extension property for every limit ordinal $\delta$.
Definition 3.1. Let $L\subset L_{1}$ be $\mu$-ary languages, $T_{1}$ an $(L_{1})_{\mu,\mu}$ theory, and $\Gamma$ be a set of $\mu$-ary $(L_{1})_{\mu,\mu}$-types. Here we define a $\mu$-ary $(L_{1})_{\mu,\mu}$-type as a set of $(L_{1})_{\mu,\mu}$ formulas in the same free variables $\mathbf{x}$, where $\mathbf{x}$ has arity less than $\mu$. We define • $\operatorname{EC}^{\mu}(T_{1},\Gamma)=\{M:M\textrm{an }L_{1}\textrm{-structure% ,}\,\,M\models T_{1},M\textrm{omits each type in }\Gamma\}$ • $\operatorname{PC}^{\mu}(T_{1},\Gamma,L)=\{M\upharpoonright L:M\in\operatorname% {EC}^{\mu}(T_{1},\Gamma)\}$
Definition 2.4. Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ be a $\mu$-AEC with $L=\operatorname{L}(\operatorname{\mathcal{K}})$ and let $\widehat{L}$ be a $\lambda$-ary expansion of $L$ with $\lambda\geq\mu$. A $\lambda$-ary $\widehat{L}$-abstract Morleyization of $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$ is a class $\widehat{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}$ of $\widehat{L}$-structures satisfying: (1) The map $\widehat{M}\mapsto\widehat{M}\upharpoonright L$ is a bijection from $\widehat{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}$ onto $\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$. For $M\in\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}$, we write $\widehat{M}$ for the unique element of $\widehat{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}$ whose reduct is $M$. (2) Invariance: If $f:M\cong N$, then $f:\widehat{M}\cong\widehat{N}$. (3) Monotonicity: If $M\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}N$, then $\widehat{M}\subseteq\widehat{N}$. We occasionally omit the “abstract” and simply speak of a Morleyization, provided there is no risk of confusion. We order $\widehat{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}$ by $\widehat{M}\leq_{\widehat{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}}\widehat{N}$ if and only if $M\leq_{\operatorname{\mathcal{K}}}N$.
